      <h3>Vulnerability Analysis</h3>

      <div class="callout callout-vuln">
        <div class="callout-title">&#x1f6a8; Vulnerability: Double-Free in Tcache</div>
        The <code class="inline">free</code> operation frees <code class="inline">GLOBAL_BUFFER</code> but <strong>does NOT NULL out the pointer</strong>. The only guard is <code class="inline">if (idx &lt; 8)</code>, which limits total frees to 8 &mdash; but this does <strong>not</strong> prevent freeing the same chunk twice! In glibc 2.27, tcache has <strong>no double-free detection</strong> (the <code class="inline">tcache_key</code> check was added in 2.29). This means:<br>
        &bull; We can call <code class="inline">free()</code> on the same chunk consecutively<br>
        &bull; The tcache freelist becomes: <code class="inline">chunk &rarr; chunk</code> (self-referencing cycle)<br>
        &bull; We can then allocate from tcache, overwrite the FD pointer, and achieve <strong>tcache poisoning</strong><br>
        &bull; This lets us allocate at <strong>any address</strong> we choose
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-title">&#x26a0;&#xfe0f; Constraint: Size &lt; 0x100</div>
        The <code class="inline">allocate_buffer</code> function enforces <code class="inline">__size &lt; 0x100</code>, limiting us to tcache-sized chunks (up to 0xF0 usable = 0x100 chunk with header). We cannot directly create unsorted-bin-sized chunks through <code class="inline">malloc</code>. However, we can still get chunks into the unsorted bin by forging a <strong>fake large chunk</strong> in BSS and freeing it via tcache poisoning.
